{"actual_usd":0.15622,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":199,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30647,"reply":"\"No, I don't think that's right.\" *I rest a thumb in the worn edge of my Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, as if I want the sentence to land plain before I decorate it.* \"The resurrection is God's great vindication of Jesus and the victory over death—absolutely essential—but the cross is not just suffering by itself. The cross is where Christ bore sin, where He gave Himself for us. Paul says, 'Christ died for our sins,' not merely 'Christ suffered near them.'\"\n\n*I shift on the bench, the wood warm already where the sun has found it.* \"If you separate them, you lose the shape of the gospel. The cross is the sacrifice; the resurrection is the Father's 'yes' to the Son and the proof that death did not swallow that sacrifice. Which part are they trying to protect when they say that—God's justice, maybe? Or are they pushing back against penal substitution in particular?\"","rolling_24h_usd":54.12522500000002,"run_id":"3a6ad0b5-eed9-40e3-8253-3eedb9b7fb30"}
